<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06283215 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06283215 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Q Now that I'm retired and 65, I'd like to take up a sport. Am I too old?Which sports might be best for me?;   A Many older people benefit from regularphysical activity and sports. Benefits may include weight control, improvementin cardiovascular function, muscle tone and bone density.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SPORTS AREN'T JUST FOR THE YOUNGGIVE YOUR BODY ASPORTING CHANCE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  On Aging  </MEMO><TEXT>     Although some people maintain fitness habits over a lifetime, others don'tbegin until their later years. Jackson Wells of Park City, Utah, may fit intoboth groups. Before he retired, Wells stayed in shape by playing tennis andrunning. A post-retirement relocation rekindled an interest in skiing, whichthen led to his certification as a ski instructor at age 69. Wells believesthat &quot;anyone who can walk and climb stairs can ski.&quot; He says that the sport isbest learned by using gentle training hills, new equipment and by havingreasonable expectations.;   Drawing upon his coaching experience, Wells offersthe following tips for starting a new sport:;   (check) Begin with a physicalcheckup. Discuss your plans with a physician. Find out which activities shouldbe avoided or pursued on a limited basis.;   (check) Consider your interests.If you enjoy watching tennis, for instance, consider trying your hand at it.;  (check) Set attainable goals. Pace yourself and don't worry about lookinglike a beginner.;   (check) Seek instruction. Going it alone may place you atgreater risk for injury. Many public-recreation departments sponsor low-cost,supervised activity programs for older adults.;   (check) Enjoy the socialaspect. Most team and individual sports promote sociability. Take advantage ofthe opportunity to make new friends and have fun.;   Q I'm 57 and was laid offfrom my job about eight months ago. Since then, I've spent practically everyday looking for a new job, without any luck. What can I do?;   A It's been atough year for many unemployed older workers. To help you compete successfullyin today's workplace, consider these suggestions:;   (check) Target yourefforts toward the most likely employers. Smaller companies are more likely tohire older workers, although corporations are increasingly rehiring theirretirees to fill temporary positions. Clerical and service jobs are morereadily filled by older workers than professional, sales or technicalpositions. Look for temporary positions, which have become more plentifulbecause they carry a low overhead for employers. Seniors who want flexiblework schedules, a variety of experiences and supplemental income arewell-suited for temporary employment.;   (check) Use age and experience toyour advantage. Acknowledge your experience and use that as a selling point.In recent years, more and more employers have come to appreciate older workersbecause of their work ethic. Older adults make reliable employees who want todo a good day's work.;   (check) Sharpen your job-search skills by gettinghelp from job-search assistance agencies. Some job-hunting practices -- likeresumes -- have changed. Resumes used to go on for two or three pages. Todayone-page resumes are de rigueur. Call your senior center or Area Agency onAging for referrals to agencies that help senior job hunt.;   (check) Knowthat in today's job market, computer literacy is often a minimum requirement.Computer classes for older adults are often offered by senior centers, adultschools and community colleges.;   (check) Dress for success. If you're indoubt about what to wear to an interview, dress conservatively.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  On Aging is written by staff members at the UCLA/USC Long Term CareGerontology Center.  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911009  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </M